t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\">-9</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\">Glenn Beck</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\">10%</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\">24%</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\">-14</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Rush Limbaugh</strong></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>12</strong>%</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>39</strong>%</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"vertical-align:middle\">\r\n\t\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>-27</strong></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So while it&rsquo;s largely correct to conclude that Limbaugh&rsquo;s program is the &quot;least-trusted,&quot; the same cannot be as easily said about Fox News. Within cable news, Fox News rates last, but in a broader pool, it fares better. (<a href=\"http://www.politifact.com/punditfact/article/2014/oct/21/pew-study-finds-rush-limbaugh-least-trustworthy-ne/\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>We noted the Pew findings</u></a> and called Limbaugh the &quot;least trustworthy&quot; news source in an Oct. 21 article. We did not do the same with Fox News.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&lsquo;Most popular&rsquo;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As for measuring popularity -- by the number of listeners, viewers or readers -- that can be complicated. For starters, the Pew survey includes newspapers, broadcast TV networks, cable TV networks, websites, radio organizations and individual radio shows.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pitts expanded upon his claim in terms of comparing Limbaugh to other radio programs and Fox News to other cable networks. We think that&rsquo;s a fair metric.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ll take Limbaugh first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rachel Nelson with Premiere Networks, the company that distributes the <em>Rush Limbaugh Show</em>, said it is the No. 1 talk radio program in America.<strong> </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The <em>Rush Limbaugh Show</em> is heard on nearly 600 stations by up to 20 million people each week and is the highest-rated national radio talk show in America,&quot; Nelson said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, it&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/06/AR2009030603435.html\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>hard to find objective confirmation</u></a> for the size of the Limbaugh audience. In radio, the Arbitron/Nielsen Audio service is the leading source for independent data. In order to get firm statistics for Limbaugh, one would need to look at how his show performed in all of the markets where stations carry it. That has not been done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The closest approximation to Arbitron ratings comes from Talkers Magazine. <a href=\"http://www.talkers.com/top-talk-radio-audiences/\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>In October</u></a>, the magazine estimated Limbaugh&rsquo;s audience at 12.5 million or more each week. But as the magazine notes, &quot;these figures are non-scientific projections based upon a significant sample and do not represent exact Nielsen Audio or any other rating service totals.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What might compete with Limbaugh? NPR&rsquo;s<strong> </strong><em>Morning Edition</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It airs on about 660 stations and according to NPR, in the Spring 2014 survey, 12,267,800 listeners tuned in each week, using Arbitron data. (In the Pew survey, 29 percent of people said they trusted NPR, 9 percent said they distrusted the public radio broadcaster.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bob Thompson is a professor at Syracuse University&rsquo;s Newhouse School of Public Communications. Thompson said the Arbitron numbers are themselves estimates based on statistical models. Thompson said that <em>Morning Edition </em>and the <em>Rush Limbaugh Show</em> could have similar-sized audiences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Those Arbitron numbers put NPR reasonably in the range of 12.5 million people who listen that show,&quot; Thompson said. &quot;It&rsquo;s silly to look at them as exact, but they get us into the neighborhood.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In summary, most everyone agrees that Limbaugh is near the top. But a definitive figure of listeners is elusive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the television side, Pitts&rsquo; claim about Fox News popularity is right when compared to other cable news networks.<strong> </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Based on Nielsen data, in 2013, about 1.77 million viewers tuned in Fox News during the prime time hours between 8 and 11 p.m. That is more than the viewers for CNN and MSNBC combined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But we should note that<strong> </strong>all of the network news programs beat out Fox News many times over. On an average night, 8.4 million viewers chose <em>NBC Nightly News</em>, 7.7 million viewers picked <em>ABC World News</em>, and 6.5 million viewers tuned in<em> CBS Evening News</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Cable news carves up a tiny slice of the population of this country,&quot; Thompson said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Our ruling</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pitts said America&rsquo;s least-trusted news sources are also its most popular ones and focused on the <em>Rush Limbaugh Show</em> on radio and Fox News on cable. According to the survey Pitts used, Limbaugh&rsquo;s program is indeed the least-trusted news source. However, comparing the size of the gap between people who trust to those who distrust a source, Fox News falls in the middle of the pack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In terms of popularity, <em>Fox News</em> clearly<strong> </strong>is the most popular channel in its genre and the <em>Rush Limbaugh Show&nbsp;</em>is likely the most popular radio talk show (or at least very close to it).&nbsp;Pitts&rsquo; assessment also<strong> </strong>obscures the enormous reach of network television news. The lowest-performing network, CBS, has an audience three times that of Fox News.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pitts makes some valid points but he leaves out information that might lead someone to reach a different conclusion. We rate his claim<strong> </strong>Half True.</p>\r\n", "ruling_comments_date": "2014-11-06T15:21:31.718585", "ruling_date": "2014-11-06T16:16:54", "ruling_headline": "Liberal columnist says the least trusted news sources are the most popular", "ruling_headline_slug": "liberal-columnist-says-least-trusted-news-sources-", "ruling_link_text": "People both trust and distrust Fox News", "ruling_state": null, "source_documents": null, "sources": "<p>Miami Herald, <a href=\"http://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/leonard-pitts-jr/article3499672.html\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>For too many, minds closed to the truth</u></a>, Nov. 1, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pew Research, <a href=\"http://www.journalism.org/files/2014/10/Political-Polarization-and-Media-Habits-FINAL-REPORT-10-21-2014.pdf\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>Political Polarization &amp; Media Habits</u></a>, Oct. 21, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pew Research Center, <a href=\"http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2014/10/30/which-news-organization-is-the-most-trusted-the-answer-is-complicated/\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>Which news organization is the most trusted? The answer is complicated.</u></a>, Oct. 30, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Washington Post, <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/06/AR2009030603435.html\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>Limbaugh&#39;s Audience Size? It&#39;s Largely Up in the Air</u></a>, March 7, 2009</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Talkers, <a href=\"http://www.talkers.com/top-talk-radio-audiences/\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>The Top Talk Radio Audiences</u></a>, October 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TV By the Numbers, <a href=\"http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/10/28/fnc-dominates-its-cable-news-competition-in-october/320548/\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>FNC Dominates Its Cable News Competition in October</u></a>, Oct. 28, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hollywood Reporter, <a href=\"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-news-nabs-historic-cable-736624\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>Fox News Nabs Historic Cable Ratings Victory</u></a>, Sept. 30, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pew Research Center, <a href=\"http://www.journalism.org/2014/03/26/state-of-the-news-media-2014-key-indicators-in-media-and-news/#audience\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>State of the News Media 2014 - Cable</u></a>, March 26, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pew Research Center, <a href=\"http://www.journalism.org/2014/03/26/state-of-the-news-media-2014-key-indicators-in-media-and-news/#audience\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><u>State of the News Media 2014 - Network</u></a>, March 26, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Email interview, Rachel Nelson, director of public relations, Premiere Networks, Nov. 5, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Email interview, Amy Mitchell, director of journalism research, Pew Research Center, Nov. 5, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Email interview, Isabel Lara, media relations director, NPR, Nov. 5, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Email interview, Peter Jaroff, assistant professor, School of Media and Communication,Temple University, Nov. 5, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interview, Bob Thompson, professor of television and popular culture, S.I. Newhouse School of Public Communications, Syracuse University, Nov. 5, 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interview, James Webster, professor, School of Communications, Northwestern University, Nov. 5, 2014</p>\r\n", "speaker": {"adkey": null, "advalue": null, "barely_true_count": 0, "current_job": "", "false_count": 0, "fir